{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17621400","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17621400"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:53:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:53:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16708"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16708","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16708"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.67,0.19,0.05,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9399"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74845"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9399","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9399"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16708"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60351"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4625"},{"type":"tags","id":"4886"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8505"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22248"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22253"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74845","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74845"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset confusion and difficulty understanding speech. Her family reports that she is speaking fluently but not making sense. She has a history of atrial fibrillation and hypertension. Her medications include warfarin and perindopril. On examination, she appears alert but confused. Her vital signs are within normal limits. She has fluent but incomprehensible speech with frequent word substitutions. She has difficulty following simple commands. Visual field testing reveals a right upper quadrantanopia. The remainder of her neurological examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most characteristic feature of this patient\u0027s language deficit?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Poor prosody","Paraphasias","Non-fluent speech","Normal comprehension","Preserved repetition"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features consistent with Wernicke\u0027s aphasia due to a stroke affecting the posterior superior temporal gyrus (Wernicke\u0027s area). The key features include fluent but meaningless speech with impaired comprehension and frequent word substitutions (paraphasias).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParaphasias\u003C/strong\u003E are characteristic of Wernicke\u0027s aphasia and involve the substitution of inappropriate words or sounds during speech. These can be semantic (related words, e.g., \u0027chair\u0027 for \u0027table\u0027) or phonemic (similar-sounding words, e.g., \u0027cat\u0027 for \u0027hat\u0027).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPoor prosody\u003C/strong\u003E is more characteristic of Broca\u0027s aphasia, where speech is non-fluent and effortful with preserved comprehension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-fluent speech\u003C/strong\u003E is not a feature of Wernicke\u0027s aphasia. Instead, speech is typically fluent but lacks meaningful content.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal comprehension\u003C/strong\u003E is not seen in Wernicke\u0027s aphasia. Impaired comprehension is a cardinal feature due to the role of the posterior temporal lobe in language processing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPreserved repetition\u003C/strong\u003E is not characteristic of Wernicke\u0027s aphasia. Both comprehension and repetition are impaired due to damage to the posterior language areas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe associated right upper quadrantanopia is due to involvement of Meyer\u0027s loop, which carries visual fibres from the upper retinal quadrant through the temporal lobe. This helps localise the lesion to the posterior temporal region supplied by the inferior division of the middle cerebral artery.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Wernicke\u0027s aphasia is characterised by fluent but meaningless speech with poor comprehension and frequent paraphasias.","The posterior superior temporal gyrus (Wernicke\u0027s area) is supplied by the inferior division of the middle cerebral artery.","Lesions affecting the left posterior temporal lobe often cause a right upper quadrantanopia due to involvement of Meyer\u0027s loop."],"references":["Sheppard SM, Sebastian R. Diagnosing and managing post-stroke aphasia. Expert Rev Neurother. 2021 Feb;21(2):221-234. doi: 10.1080/14737175.2020.1855976. Epub 2020 Dec 10. PMID: 33231117; PMCID: PMC7880889","Howard, R., Kullmann, D., Werring, D., \u0026 Zandi, M. (Eds.). (2024). Neurology: a queen square textbook. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Tan, Y., Zhang, LM., Liang, Xl. et al. A literature review and meta-analysis of the optimal factors study of repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation in post-infarction aphasia. Eur J Med Res 29, 18 (2024). https://doi.org/10.1186/s40001-023-01525-5","Tippett DC, Niparko JK, Hillis AE. Aphasia: Current Concepts in Theory and Practice. J Neurol Transl Neurosci. 2014 Jan;2(1):1042. PMID: 24904925; PMCID: PMC4041294"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60351"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16708"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60351","links":